Religion events from around the Washington area
Local
Saturday, 9:30 a.m. to 3 p.m.: Lenten quiet day. Come for a day of meditation, quiet reflection and prayer. The Rev. John Branson, interim rector, will lead a journey through the wilderness with the Desert Fathers. Christ Church, 118 N. Washington St., Alexandria. $15 registration fee includes a morning snack, light lunch and coffee and tea. Vegetarian meals available by advance registration. parishlife@ccalex.org. Register: www.historicchristchurch.org/download_file/view/1618. 703-549-1450. www.historicchristchurch.org.
Saturday, noon to 5 p.m., and Sunday, 10:30 a.m.: 150th anniversary public forum: “Building a Just and Loving Community.” Saturday: Gary Dorrien of Union Theological Seminary in New York and Renee K. Harrison, professor of African American and U.S. religious history at Howard University’s School of Divinity, will address economic justice, progressive Christianity and economic democracy. Sunday, Alton Pollard, dean of Howard’s School of Divinity, will preach. First Congregational United Church of Christ, 945 G St. NW. Free. 202-628-4317. www.firstuccdc.org.
Saturday, 12:30 p.m.: Carillon concert. Edward M. Nassor performs Mathias van den Gheyn’s “Preludio No. 8 in A Minor.” Washington National Cathedral, Bishop’s Garden area, 3101 Wisconsin Ave. NW. Free. 202-537-6200 or www.nationalcathedral.org.
Saturday, 7 p.m.: The Duke Ellington Society will host a program of Ellington’s music and play recordings of his band’s performances. Grace Lutheran Church, 4300 16th St. NW. Free. Luvenia George, lgeogal226@aol.com or 202-723-4408.
Sundays, 8:45 a.m., and Wednesdays, 6 p.m.: Bible study. Calvary Episcopal Church, 509 I St. NE. Free. 202-546-8011.
Sundays through March 22, 9:30 to 10:15 a.m.: A Lenten series, led by seminarian Grace Pratt, will use Visio Divina (“Divine Seeing”) with the St. John’s Bible, the first handwritten illuminated Bible to be commissioned in more than 500 years. At this first meeting, “The Illuminator,” a film about the Bible, will be shown. The other four sessions will explore a different work from the St. John’s Bible using the Visio Divina method. This will be a contemplative exploration of Lent through the lens of biblical illuminations. St. George’s Episcopal Church, Parish Hall, 915 N. Oakland St., Arlington. Free-will offering. info@saintgeorgeschurch.org. 703-525-8286.
Sunday, 10 a.m.: International Women’s Day Celebration and Marketplace, themed “Make It Happen.” Human rights advocate Pauline Muchina, a native of the Rift Valley Province in Kenya, will be the guest preacher. Following the worship, all are welcome to the International Women’s Marketplace in the auditorium, where 15 vendors will sell their wares and offer food samples from various countries from 11:30 a.m. to 3 p.m.. Diane Lorenz, board chair of Empowered Women International, an organization that helps immigrant, refugee and low-income women, will be the guest speaker. Christ Church, 118 N. Washington St., Alexandria. parishlife@ccalex.org. 703-549-1450. www.historicchristchurch.org.
Sunday, 10 a.m.: “Going to Church: It’s Not What You Think!” The Rev. Susan Flanders, former rector of St. John’s Norwood in Chevy Chase and of other parishes in the diocese, will discuss her recently published memoir. St. John’s Episcopal Church, Lafayette Square, 1525 H St. NW. Free. 202-347-8766. www.stjohns-dc.org.
Sundays, 10 a.m.: Children ages 4 to 12 are invited to an ongoing guided meditation and fun activities that may inspire kindness, patience and other positive qualities. Vajrayogini Buddhist Center, 1787 Columbia Rd. NW. Ages 4 to 12, $5; 13 and older, $6. 202-986-2257. www.meditation-dc.org.
Sunday, 10 a.m.: Ugandan Kids Choir will perform traditional Ugandan songs and dances during the worship service. Concord-St. Andrew’s United Methodist Church, 5910 Goldsboro Rd., Bethesda. Donations appreciated. 301-229-3383. www.csachurch.com .
Sunday, 1 to 2 p.m.: Bible study on the Gospel of Mark, “the fastest Gospel,” hosted by the 20s&30s Group and led by cathedral seminarian Elizabeth Hadaway. Washington National Cathedral, Library Board Room on South Road, 3101 Wisconsin Ave. NW. Free. 202-537-6200. www.nationalcathedral.org. Sunday, 4 p.m.: Cathedral Choral Society concert. Guest conductor Todd Fickley leads the ensemble, soprano Stefanie Moore, baritone Andrew Sauvageau and organist J. Reilly Lewis in “French Elegy,” a performance of works by Langlais, Boulanger, Poulenc and Fauré. Washington National Cathedral, Front Nave, 3101 Wisconsin Ave. NW. $25-$75. 202-537-6200. www.nationalcathedral.org.
Sunday, 4 p.m.: Music at the Monastery. Russell Weismann performs works by Crocker, J.S. Bach, Bovet, Cooman and Louis Vierne. Franciscan Monastery, 1400 Quincy St. NE. Free. 202-526-6800, ext. 374. www.myfranciscan.com.
Sunday, 5 p.m.: Sahun Hong will perform works by Handel, Beethoven, Chopin and Brahms. Church of the Annunciation, 3810 Massachusetts Ave. NW. Free-will offering. 202-441-7678.
Sunday, 5 p.m.: Music by composers born in March. Deni Foster and Friends will perform works by J. S. Bach, Vivaldi, Teleman, Haydn, Barber and Andrew L. Webber. Paint Branch Unitarian Universalist Church, 3215 Powder Mill Rd., Adelphi. Free. 301-937-3666. www.pbuuc.org.
Sundays through April 26, 5:30 to 8 p.m.: “Rebuilding When Your Relationship Ends,” a book by Bruce Fisher. The Arlington Diocese Office for Family Life will offer a nondenominational, nonprofit rebuilding program to those who have lost their love relationship to separation, divorce or death. St. Martin De Porres Center, 4650 Taney Ave., Alexandria. Donation, $50. facilitator@copingrebuilding.com, 703-596-2673 or www.copingrebuilding.com.
Sundays, 6 p.m.: Consider a Sunday evening worship service in a less formal atmosphere and more intimate setting to help you get ready for the week ahead. Communion offered. No child care. Emmanuel Lutheran Church, 2589 Chain Bridge Rd., Vienna. 703-938-2119. www.elcvienna.org.
Sunday, 6:30 p.m.: Guitarist William Feasley presents a program on historic guitar-like instruments, including the theorbo, baroque guitar, 19th-century guitar and modern guitar. Davies Memorial Unitarian Universalist Church, 7400 Temple Hill Rd., Camp Springs. $15; ages 1 to 18, $5. 301-449-4308. www.dmuuc.org/music_daviesconcerts.html.
Most weekdays, 10:30 a.m.: Behind-the-scenes cathedral tour for ages 11 and older. See gargoyles and stained-glass windows and climb a lot of stairs to view the city from above. Washington National Cathedral, 3101 Wisconsin Ave. NW. $25; children, seniors, students and military, $21. 202-537-6200 or www.nationalcathedral.org.
Mondays, noon: “Brown Bag and Bible.” The Rev. Janice Mynchenberg leads a weekly study of the Gospel of Mark with the help of a commentary by N.T. Wright. Bring your lunch. Georgetown Lutheran Church, 1556 Wisconsin Ave. NW. Free. 202-337-9070. www.byfaithhopelove.com/GTL.
Mondays through March 23, 6:30 p.m.: The Rev. James Martin will discuss an archaeological site visited by him and also the key gospel story associated with that sacred place, inviting us to pray with him at key sites and key moments in Jesus’s life. Each session will close with a guided Ignatian meditation. Washington National Cathedral, Sayre House, South Road NW. Free. mlewallen@cathedral.org. 202-537-6200. www.nationalcathedral.org.
Mondays, 7 p.m.: Monday night worship services feature a less formal atmosphere in a somewhat smaller setting at a more convenient or comfortable day and time. Celebration of Holy Communion, with refreshments following the worship. Child care available. Lutheran Church of St. Andrew, 15300 New Hampshire Ave., Silver Spring. info@mystandrew.org. 301-384-4394. www.mystandrew.org.
Mondays, 7 p.m.: Sally Jones leads “A Course in Miracles.” Davies Memorial Unitarian Universalist Church, 7400 Temple Hills Rd., Camp Springs. Free. 301-449-4308. www.dmuuc.org.
Mondays, 7 p.m.: Kirsten Norris leads yoga sessions. Bring a mat. Pilgrim Church United Church of Christ, Social Hall, 2206 Briggs Rd., Silver Spring. Suggested donation, $5 to $10. The Rev. Jessie Lowry, jessdoerrer@gmail.com or 877-792-8479.
Tuesdays and Thursdays, 9:15 a.m.: Senior Fit, an exercise class for ages 55 and older to build strength, fitness and cardiovascular health. Required physician-consent form is available at the information center or by visiting the Web site. Lutheran Church of St. Andrew, 15300 New Hampshire Ave., Silver Spring. Free. Call Marilee at 301-384-4394 or go to www.mystandrew.org.
Tuesdays, 10:45 a.m.: “Spiritual Reflections” tour. A one-hour, docent-led tour explores stories of faithful action and devotion highlighted in glass and stone. Tours include stories, silence, poetry, prayer and reflective invitations, including one to attend Eucharist at noon. Participants will receive a pilgrimage medallion. Tours do not take place on holidays or during special events. Washington National Cathedral, Wisconsin and Massachusetts avenues NW. $15. Questions: Pilgrimages@cathedral.org, 202-537-6200 or www.nationalcathedral.org.
Tuesday, 12:10 p.m.: Classical music concert. Violinist Elizabeth Adams and pianist Sam Post perform works by subversive geniuses Schubert, Shostakovich and Schnittke. Church of the Epiphany, 1317 G St. NW. Suggested donation, $10. 202-347-2635, ext. 20.
Tuesday and Wednesday, 1:30 p.m.: Cathedral tour and tea. A docent will lead a tour of the cathedral, explaining its history, architecture and art — plus a traditional English tea and a scenic view of the city from the cathedral tower. On Wednesday, the tour will focus on the stained-glass windows. Washington National Cathedral, docent station at the Rear Nave, Wisconsin and Massachusetts avenues NW. $30; reservations required. 202-537-8993, www.allhallowsguild.org or misbister@cathedral.org.
Tuesdays through March 24, 6:30 to 8:30 p.m.: Join fellow St. Georgians and members of the other Episcopal churches in Arlington for soup and salad followed by Bible study that begins at 7:15 p.m. Study of the Letter to the Hebrews will be led by the Rev. Katherine Grieb, professor at Virginia Theological Seminary. It is based on “Conversation with Scripture,” Grieb’s book on the Letter to the Hebrews. St. George’s Episcopal Church, Parish Hall, 915 N. Oakland St., Arlington. Free-will offering. info@saintgeorgeschurch.org or 703-525-8286.
Tuesdays through March 24, 7 to 9 p.m.: “And the Greatest of These Is Love.” Harvey Bale, who recently earned a master’s of arts degree in theology and New Testament studies from Virginia Theological Seminary, will facilitate the study group in its consideration of community life after Christ’s death, Christian leadership, neighborly concern and more. Washington National Cathedral, South Tower, 3101 Wisconsin Ave. NW. 202-537-6200. www.nationalcathedral.org. Free, but please register at mlewallen@ cathedral.org.
Tuesdays, 7 to 8:30 p.m.: Homework Helpers invites parents or guardians to bring their children in grades 1 to 8 for free after-school tutoring, advice and homework help. The program is certified by the Episcopal Diocese of Washington under its mandatory “Safeguarding God’s Children” training. St. John’s Church, Broadcreek, Bayne Hall, 9801 Livingston Rd., Fort Washington. Free. Registration: Ruth LaBelle, program director, at 240-461-5330 or hwhelpers@stjohnsbroadcreek.org.
Tuesdays, 7 to 8:30 p.m.: Rabbi Susan Grossman will speak about “Parting of the Ways: How Judaism and Christianity Became Two.” Beth Shalom Congregation, 8070 Harriet Tubman Lane, Columbia. $20. 410-531-5115. www.beth-shalom.net.
Tuesdays, 7 to 9 p.m.: “Passages.” A 14-week program for people struggling with separation or divorce. Vienna Presbyterian Church, 124 Park St. NE, Vienna. Program is free; materials cost $20 (scholarships available). Register at Passages@ViennaPres.org. 703-938-9050 or www.viennapres.org.
Wednesdays, noon, and Fridays, 6 p.m.: Stations of the Cross. Calvary Episcopal Church, 509 I St. NE. Free. 202-546-8011.
Wednesdays through April 1, noon to 1 p.m.: “Soup and Devotion” luncheons. Homemade soup and dessert with singing, praying and “following Jesus” devotions. Proceeds from a good-will offering will go to Imagine No Malaria, a campaign of the United Methodist Church to save millions of lives in Africa. Glenn Dale United Methodist Church, 8600 Springfield Rd., Glenn Dale. 301-262-2299.
Wednesday through April 1, noon: “Days of Simplicity,” a series of Lenten concerts featuring local artists. A lunch of soup and bread follows. Christ Congregational Church, 9525 Colesville Rd., Silver Spring. Free-will offering. 301-585-8010. www.cccsilverspring.org.
Wednesdays through April 1, 5:15 p.m.: Lenten reflection series themed “Pathways to God.” After the 5:15 Mass, the Most Reverend James Keleher, archbishop emeritus of Kansas City, Kan., will present “Baptism: Our Consecration through the Blood of Christ and the Power of the Holy Spirit.” All are welcome. A full list of topics and presenters may be found at www.nationalshrine.com/lent. Basilica of the National Shrine of the Immaculate Conception, 400 Michigan Ave. NE. Free. 202-526-8300.
Wednesday, 6 to 8:15 p.m.: Walk the labyrinth from 6 to 7:30 p.m., then attend a Taize prayer service at 7:30 p.m. St. George’s Episcopal Church, 915 N. Oakland St., Arlington. Free. bkeseley@saintgeorgeschurch.org. 703-525-8286.
Wednesdays through March 18, 6:30 p.m.: “The Psalms: The Journey from the Blues to Joy!” The Lenten program continues with a simple supper at 6:30 p.m. and a presentation of various jazz and blues compositions of Psalms by pianist and composer Katherine Chrishon at 7 p.m. Participants will be able to write their own Lament Psalm and sing it in blues style. All are welcome. St. Aidan’s Episcopal Church, 8531 Riverside Rd., Alexandria. Free, donations welcome. revmthumphrey@gmail.com. 703-360-4220. www.staidansepiscopal.com.
Wednesdays through March 25, 6:30 to 8 p.m.: Lenten potluck series. Students of all ages are invited to share dinner; studies titled “Waxing Poetic,” led by the rector; “Holy Week Through Icons,” led by a seminarian; and worship services. The youngest students will study the Ten Commandments as the teens create a new banner. Child care is offered during the class sessions. The concluding worship service will incorporate Celtic prayers and music. A healing service follows at 8 p.m. Historic Pohick Episcopal Church, Colonial Parish of George Washington, 9301 Richmond Hwy., Lorton. 703-339-6572. www.pohick.org.
Wednesdays, 7 p.m.: Tai chi classes. Certified instructor will teach the advanced and intermediate-level classes in the movement discipline, which may strengthen the mind and body. Davies Memorial Unitarian Universalist Church, 7400 Temple Hills Rd., Camp Springs. Suggested donation, $5. 301-449-4308. www.dmuuc.org.
Wednesday, 7:30 p.m.: Lenten Bible study. Pastor Matt Braddock will lead a discussion of Bruce Epperly’s book, “Healing Marks,” about the healing miracles in Mark’s Gospel. Christ Congregational Church, 9525 Colesville Rd., Silver Spring. Free. 301-585-8010. www.cccsilverspring.org.
Wednesdays, Fridays and Saturdays: High school students are invited to earn their community service credits by volunteering at the Fort Washington Food Pantry. St. John’s Episcopal Church, Broad Creek, 9801 Livingston Rd., Fort Washington. 301-248-4290. www.stjohnsbroadcreek.org.
Thursdays, 7:30 to 8:30 a.m.: Breakfast Bible study. A reading and discussion of the Bible readings for the upcoming Sunday, according to the Revised Common Lectionary. Open to the public. Sponsored by St. Nicholas Episcopal Church. IHOP, 20009 Century Blvd., Germantown. info@saintnicks.com or 240-631-2800.
Thursdays, 4 p.m.: Bible study. The Worship Center, 99 Adams St., Manassas. Free. 571-283-3252.
Thursdays through March 26, 6:30 p.m.: Soup suppers and Lenten vesper worship services. All are welcome. Grace Lutheran Church, 10928 Indian Head Hwy., Fort Washington. Donations appreciated. Grace.LutheranChurch@verizon.net or 301-292-2232.
Thursdays through March 12, 7 to 8:30 p.m.: Bible study series taught by the Rev. Stephen Rorke. St. John’s Episcopal Church, Broad Creek, 9801 Livingston Rd., Fort Washington. 301-248-4290. www.stjohnsbroadcreek.org.
Friday, Noon: Ian Boxall, associate professor of the New Testament at Catholic University, presents “Out of the Shadows: Mary in the New Testament and Beyond.” The lecture is co-sponsored by Catholic University. National Museum of Women in the Arts, 1250 New York Ave. Free. 202-783-5000.
Friday, 12:15 to 1 p.m.: Arts at midday. Pianist and organist Sonya Sutton will perform a program of music for meditation by Chopin, J.S. Bach, Glass, Pärt and Barber. St. Alban’s Episcopal Church, 3001 Wisconsin Ave. NW. Free. 202-363-8286 or www.StAlbansDC.org.
Friday, 12:15 to 1 p.m.: Classical pipe organist Vincent Carr will perform works by Antonio Soler, E. Power Biggs, Florence B. Price, Craig Phillips, Derek Bourgeois, Egil Hovland and a piece by the organist. National City Christian Church, 5 Thomas Cir. NW. Free, donations welcome. 202-797-0103.
Friday, 5:45 to 9:30 p.m.: Shabbat Across the Americas, a celebration of the the Latin roots of American Jewry with programming for all ages. Dinner will consist of a meat inspired by South American tradition. Vegan and vegetarian options are available. During the 8 p.m. Shabbat service, Rabbi Susan Grossman will share tales of how Jews fleeing the Spanish Inquisition made their way from South America to found the earliest Jewish communities in North America. Refreshments will follow. Beth Shalom Congregation, 8070 Harriet Tubman Lane, Columbia. Free; visit Web site for dinner pricing and reservations. 410-531-5115. www.beth-shalom.net.
March 14, 8:30 a.m. to noon: Volunteers are needed to participate in a Stop Hunger Now meal-packaging event. Packaged meals will be sent to areas of the world where food is scarce. Annandale United Methodist Church, 6935 Columbia Pike, Annandale. 703-256-8330.
March 14, 9:30 a.m. to 3 p.m.: Bishop Carolyn Tanner Irish will lead a Lenten quiet day where all may open themselves more deeply to God’s presence. This quiet day offers reflection, quiet prayer, journaling and sharing, and concludes with Holy Communion. Tanner is a public advocate for environmental causes, immigration reform, and the safety and care of children. Bring a notebook or journal and a brown bag lunch. Washington National Cathedral, Nave and Center for Prayer and Pilgrimage, 3101 Wisconsin Ave. NW. $45 if registering by March 13; $55 walk-in on March 14. E-mail pilgrimages@cathedral.org. Questions: Tiffany Montavon, tmontavon@cathedral.org. 202-537-6200. www.nationalcathedral.org.
March 14, 12:30 p.m.: Carillon concert. Edward M. Nassor performs Mathias van den Gheyn’s “Preludio No. 10 in C Major.” Washington National Cathedral, Bishop’s Garden area, 3101 Wisconsin Ave. NW. Free.202-537-6200 or www.nationalcathedral.org.
March 14, 7 p.m.: The Washington Temple Orchestra will perform classical dance pieces. Features Clarissa Lindsay in Rosauro’s “Marima Concerto”; also on the program are Brahms’s “Hungarian Dance No. 5,” Copland’s hoedown movement from “Rodeo,” Faure’s “Pavanne,” Saint-Saens’s “Bachanalle” and Tchaikovsky’s waltz from “Sleeping Beauty.” Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, Washington Temple Visitors Center, 9900 Stoneybrook Dr., Kensington. Free. 301-587-0144.
March 14, 7 p.m.: “An Evening of Gospel and Jazz,” featuring the Pete BarenBregge Quintet and vocalist Juanita Williams. A reception with food and fellowship with the musicians will follow. St. Paul’s Moravian Church, 8505 Heathermore Blvd., Upper Marlboro. $20. 301-627-4200. www.spmoravian.org.
March 14, 7:30 p.m., and March 15, 4 p.m.: The Capital City Symphony and the Capitol Hill Chorale perform Fauré’s “Requiem,” Stephen Paulus’s “When Music Sounds,” John Tavener’s “Song for Athene” and Christopher Theofinidas’s “Rainbow Body.” Capitol Hill Presbyterian Church, 201 Independence Ave. SE. $25, preferred seating; $20, general seating; $15, ages 17 to 30; ages 16 and younger, free. 202-540-0547. www.capitolhillchorage.org.
